# 🧠 What is Consistent Hashing?

Consistent hashing is a technique used to distribute data across servers in a way that **minimizes data movement when servers are added or removed**.
Instead of reassigning all data, only a small portion of data gets redistributed.

📌 Example:
If 1 server is added, only nearby data moves instead of reshuffling everything.


# ⚠️ Problem with Traditional Hashing

Traditional hashing uses `hash(key) % N`, so when N changes (add/remove server), **almost all data gets reassigned**.
This causes cache loss, session loss, and high system load.

📌 Example:
5 servers → mod 5
Add 1 server → mod 6 → almost all users shift to new servers


# 🔁 How Consistent Hashing Works

Consistent hashing maps both **servers and data (keys)** onto a circular structure called a **hash ring**.
Each key is assigned to the next server in clockwise direction.

📌 Example:
Key = 40 → next server at 50 → stored there


# 🎯 Key Insight

Only nearby keys move when a server changes, not the entire system.
This makes it highly scalable and efficient for distributed systems.


# ➕ Adding a Server

When a new server is added, it only takes over a **small portion of data from its neighbor**.
Other servers remain unaffected.

📌 Example:
New server between S1 and S2 → only S2 loses some data


# ➖ Removing a Server

When a server fails, only its data is reassigned to the **next server in the ring**.
Rest of the system continues normally.

📌 Example:
S4 fails → its data moves to S3


# ⚠️ Problem in Basic Consistent Hashing

If servers are unevenly placed on the ring, **data distribution becomes unbalanced**, creating hotspots.
Also, when a server fails, its neighbor gets overloaded.

📌 Example:
If S1 and S2 are close → S3 handles most data


# 🧩 What are Virtual Nodes (VNodes)?

Virtual nodes mean each physical server is represented **multiple times on the hash ring**, instead of just once.
This spreads data more evenly and improves load balancing.

📌 Example:
Instead of S1 → 1 position
S1 → S1-1, S1-2, S1-3 (multiple positions)


# 🔁 How Virtual Nodes Work

Each server is hashed multiple times and placed at different positions on the ring.
Requests go to nearest virtual node, which maps back to actual server.

📌 Example:
Key → hits S1-2 → goes to server S1


# 🚀 Why Virtual Nodes are Important

They ensure **even data distribution** and reduce load imbalance across servers.
They also improve fault tolerance when a server fails.

📌 Example:
If S1 fails → its load is split across many servers instead of one


# ⚔️ Without vs With Virtual Nodes

Without VNodes → uneven distribution + hotspots
With VNodes → balanced distribution + better scaling

📌 Example:
Without → S2 overloaded
With → load shared across S2, S3, S4

